How many cops does it take to fix a light bulb? They don’t! They arrest the light bulb for being broke and beat the room for being black
.
What is the light bulb holding on to?
.
LindoYes x @ux.chanch x @stephensperry  collaboration 
.
Conceptualize and Storyboard by LindoYes
Illustrated by @ux.chanch 
Music by @stephensperry 
.
[Image ID: Police arresting a broken light bulb while other officers hit dark room with night stick. Overlapping text that says “ How many cops do it take to fix a light bulb? They don’t! They arrest the light bulb for being broke and beat the room for being black” ] 
.
#illustration #policestate #policebrutality #politicalart #comicart

[More Detailed Post] There are many stories I hold of my mom. She being a power ranger, overcoming PTSD from fighting for Zordan while raising us is one of many. 
.
Mourning my mom I found myself in day dreams of  what her actions would’ve been if she was alive. At this point in my life I have so many memories, and journal entries (she left me her journals from the late 80s til 11/6/22) from my mom. I feel confident I know.
.
This weekend I made some bad and irrational decisions. I didn’t cause harm to myself or finances but it left me feeling terrible. All the emotions that I thought I either settle or compartmentalize I felt all at once. I regret all I did in my visit to Baltimore. It was escapist act for me but it overwhelmed me to tears. I cried for hours. 
.
I been acting like I  moved forward when I really haven’t accepted it. My therapist said I am going thru what they called anticipation grief because I will think of a future of my mom being present then sadly remember she is dead. I am working on the house she left me, a comic book, and list of other things that I think about my mom being around for. Then, I happy by the idea of that interaction to sharply become in tears knowing the truth. 
.
If it wasn’t on autopay, it didn’t get paid! I am grateful I became a super adult before my mom died. All my essential bills (food, shelter, utilities and car fares) been paid but I neglected so many other bills. I am not in debt. They got paid but I felt so embarrassed and ashamed that I had to be reminded about them. I got stuck in that day dream and lived there for too long. Too long being a month and half and going. 
.
I moved. My mom left me the house and I been living there since November. My mom died on a Sunday and that following Tuesday I became a homeowner of house filled with more memories than one generation of our family. Thankful, all that helped me clean, donate, fix and coordinate space to chill. 
.
Depress as phuck
.

I have been holding all these feelings, when i just want to be held, feel I got more heart than feelings at times, that my pride won't allow me to admit, I want to be felt, held with no letting go when I want to let go, irony of how freeing it is to be captured in someone arms as a photographer would parents with a child
.
Bringing in the new year without my mom is sickening. I  am feeling all this anxiety about interacting with folx while experiencing grief. Worry how much I can do without her and burden with all I have to do without her
.
I got 186 unanswer messages from folx  checking in, sending advice, and condolences. I haven’t had the heart to filter thru them and message back. 
.
What else have I neglected? More that I regret. I need help fixing doors in my house, brake fix on my bike and my heart. I need compliments! 
.
I have been seeing a therapist weekly.  Drinking water in the morning. Eating food that brought us together with my mom. 
.
Depress and Anxious as Phuck! 
.

I am reminded how caregiving is life long as I accept I no longer have a parent. As their life is gone. I struggled with all that’s going to happen to my life that I won’t share with them. My therapist told me to write, cry, and put off what I can until I can. Appreciate my therapist, after being on a waiting list for 7months to get a therapist because of the healthcare system. In November I decided once my mom died to reach outside of my insurance network to find one. I did find one within a week. They made me feel heard, seen, and act on the changes I need moving forward. They were able to take me until January without payment and able to  take me on income basis of $25 per session. 
I am just started booking shows and projects to get income. So, i am asking for $300 to cover the next 12 sessions.
.

“He looked so much like me when I saw him, I thought I died” 
1. There is a form of PTSD called “linked fate” where a person or people see themselves so acceptable to a tragedy they lived with it as it directly happen to them. That’s why that line hit above 
2. Them dropping the footage on Friday is tactful for it to be suppress in the news cycle 
3. The only changed I can track in police brutality since I learned about Sean Bell, being murdered by police is the number of bullets
4.  Police Brutality is Gang Violence which is Gun Violence, policing should be a part these convoys 
5. The police that murdered #tyrenichols were trained professionals surrounded by other trained individuals that didn’t intervene 
6. If Tyre Nichols, lived after that police brutality they would have to pay fines, imprisonment, court fees, lost of wages/employment, and healed from the wounds. 
7. Asking for diversity in policing is asking Representation in White Supremacy. 
8. Check in on me. #ElijahMcclain still on my mind. 
9. This poem is specific to #TrayvonMartin

With more stories than the tallest buildings, we are building with joy 🥲 
.
Receiving the “Jackie Robinson” award I cried during my acceptance speech. So much so my contacts fell out. A lot tears came from the realization that folx notice both the work and results. That cried was a relief from all the doubt I had about what I could do being dyslexic, opt-out of college, with seasonal depression and social anxiety could do. People ask me how was it to get the “Jackie Robinson” award and I never have a true answer beside how elated I felt. The truest answer is Joyous!
.

#TBT Skydive 🪂 I am dyslexic so I choose not to write down my poetry. I memorize as I create. I find it easier bc I often feel I am just narrating memories to an audience anyway. So when you see videos like this with visual effects. It is closer to how I see my poetry in my head as I perform. 
(I actually have aversion to all lengthy writing but that’s a story for another day) also, this poem is not about one heartbreak I actually pulled from a few 
.

Today this is direct response to #LanceReddick but it will always even now a response to black people not being able to grow and die of old age bc of systemic neglect that leads to lack of healthcare, resources and wages that allows for good quality of life.  If it’s not that it is police brutality, stressors from all the isms or the societal pressures to over perform that make us be neglectful to needs and health in order to live. My mom died before she was ever able to retire  or feel grays in hair. Black people dying before they are able experience the fullness of old age is too common .  Then to us that live on we have a form of PTSD called “linked fate” where we see ourselves dying too soon bc this is a collective experience. I have talked to my therapist about how i know i sleep in a room that my mom died in and think of my own death (a story for another post). We deserve universal healthcare, universal basic income and housing for all to increase our living expectations. The cost of these things are as much as we gave in billions for wars. I cry 😢 and sigh 😔 that we could do better bc we have the answers but  the way oppression is setup. Ugh.
.
.
[Image ID: Two faceless figures leaning on each other with light brown background] 
.
#poem #poetry #spokenword

I received the Black History Now Jackie Robinson Award! Momma, I made it! Please leave all congratulations and praise in the comments. I use that energy to stay motivated! Thank you @colorofchange for the recognition 
.
I often feel alienated in my joy because I am in some form of isolation after a performance or project. No matter if I feel good about my performance or project that fact that hold that joy alone makes me feel I am unworthy of that happiness because I am not sharing it. So, I been intentional about people hanging out with me after a show of celebratory gatherings. So this is ask virtually of sharing a few words of rejoice. This is a big accomplishment for me and I feel sad I don’t get to let my mom know.
.

2. Racism is systemic! That’s why it not enough to hold people accountable but systems as well. Because even when racists suffer consequences they still benefit from systems. The Starbucks manger was awarded more than the two black men who where profile, humiliated, harassed and lost an opportunity.

How they can put dirt on us 
and we still grow 
Drown us in water and we survive 
Planted in everything that keeps us grounded

hoping we wither

Be photosynthesis 
The sun be our best friend 
Aint flowers the blackest shit ever

Tears make up the faces of those, the morning
after, that see the sunset on a garden, full of
roses that grew from the concrete, that leave
petals on the pavement, we are, who we are,
is the church, so we lead in prayer, that we can bulletproof
all our people, while laws allow access to bullets
that can pierce through bulletproof vests,
We walk around like vets with PTSD because there’s
more gun violence here than any other war,  this
is for those that understand easy access, likelihood
of violence, and close vicinity leads to so much
loss, ask any woman that has survived an abusive relationship, Or those, that had a temporary crisis that was grateful, that they didn’t have easy access to put their
hands around a trigger, instead of holding a hand
of someone that cares to tell them why they’re
living and what they have to live for, this is for
for those that understand it’s not about just
having too much crime, but how lethal the crime is,
Because you’re likely to lose your belongings
and your life at the same time.
There’s so much loss.
That’s why we have the hashtags, the tattoos,
the shirts and remembering of the loss. We have
got so used to the loss, that we have lost ourself
only to find ourself losing more, and it’s not
a question of do we have the answers, it’s more
so can we be the resolve, to look at the garden
full of roses as much as we look at this art on
the wall
.
[Video ID: Lindo standing in front of microphone] 
.

Gumball Machine is stage play with a series of poems, animations and monologues that are based on my experiences dealing with anxiety, depression, heart break, gang culture, police harassment, flowers, therapy and black joy. All these poems and monologues speak to the motivation behind the 5 Poetry Gumball Machines across Philly that are free to use gumball machine that dispense short poems, wearable art and information of the 24/7 mental health hotline 988.

Dear Mom,

I finished making the  comic book i bragged so much to you about. Yes, your son that was so dyslexic couldn’t write a complete sentence without headaches and typos. I regret you are not here to see it. You occupy so much of my thoughts as i wonder what you would say. It been close to a year i am fighting to keep your house. I been to so many grief circles and they say things like this take time. I am scared. I fear I am not doing right by you and cry when I don’t know what that is. I read books on grief, got therapy, and cry to recognize grief come in so many forms. Grief sits with me as a shadow as big as the light i shine on it. I hope to shine so much light on it goes away. But thats dumb because shining a light on it only reveals how much i am standing in front of the light. I am as much of this grief as the shadow is a silhouette of me. 

Does that make sense. Shit i cant poet jn moments like this.

I want to say thank you to everybody for reaching out as I go through this grief. Thanks for pouring into me.
.
[Video ID: Lindo standing in kitchen with argument crown over his head]

My mom died November 6th! It’s actually not easier to deal with that death. Mainly because I thought after the funeral I figure all would be resolved. It hitting a year and I am still having the same fights I had months after her pasting. Also, miss her and feel guilty that I didn’t share how much impact she had on my career and life while she was alive. One of my rules is not to talk about family and friends on social media explicitly. I am breaking that rule to speak on my mom.
.
1. i often will wear my mom’s socks, bonnets, facemasks to feel closer to her.
2. I think how much my mom helped me with my bike when i had flat tires or needed to get it repair. My bike is main source of transportation so her helping me was impactful to commuting 
3. This weekend I refilled the the South Philly Poetry Machine which my mom helped me to do by driving me part of the way while at work
4. The only piece of art i have dedicated to her so far after her death.
5. Last picture I took with my mom
.
I am not well. I cry as I feel, I rejoice in those tears as every part of me wanted better for her. I also rejoice knowing more about my grief because all the aide i have received. 
.

OPPORTUNITY: The Museum for Art in Wood and Poet LindoYes (@lindoyes) are searching for an artist in Greater Philadelphia to create a wooden gumball machine to house capsules made from walnut shells holding original poems. The selected artist will receive a stipend and a small budget to cover supplies. Submissions will be judged based on the attractiveness of the proposal, feasibility of the project for installation and public use, and the overall creativity of the approach. The deadline to apply for consideration is November 8, 2023.

😞 As it approaches, November 6th,  marks one year of my mom’s death 💐 i have phases of denial where i tell myself she’s at the hospital or she’s out of town.  Only to scold myself for lying 🤥 
.
What Have I Been Doing In My Grief? 
Therapy bi-weekly 
Grief Circles
Dance classes 3-4 times  a week
Chilling with the homies regularly 
Biking 60% time I need to travel
Creating Art
Having folx negotiate contracts for me 
Cleaning to reset spaces
Cooking more 
.
What you can do for me? Show up for my art by attending my virtual event Nov 10th ask me to send you the link and leaving words of encouragement in the comments
.

.
#pink #poem #spokenword #grief

In mourning, Today is the day. So I will break another rule and may get curse out by my family so this will be a temporary post.
.
Today is the death of my mom. It is her death anniversary. One year, and i feel unmoved in ways i hope to have moved on by now.  So, here me hosting my mom funeral and excerpt from the speech I gave.  There is a poem reflecting of this being one year. There all the things I have been doing to grieve and a picture of me smiling at the funeral. 
. 
Want to help me grieve leave in comment encouraging words and if you interested ask me to send you the link to my virtual event about Poetry Gumball Machine which is inspired by my mom lifelong nursing career and how i translated that work into my community organizing. 
.
Today is a day of mourning for me so i will take atleast 3days before responding to comments but i will respond to everyone 
.
#poem #grief #poet

I think it’s dope when I see folx I follow post their Spotify numbers. As spoken word poets I don’t think we get to do the same because so much of our work is live performances. So here I am doing something I think is similar and allow me to reflect on my year
.
2023  I spent the first quarter mourning my mom so I spent much of the year cleaning and grieving. I look back and wonder how much of  the year would’ve been different if I didn’t lose my mom. Then, I accept I can’t change time and can only impact how it move forward. 
.
Deeper analysis of my year in my story around 4pm EST.
